

# The Elf of Room 4B

Every morning, I wake up before the sun. Not because I want to, but because the trees outside my window whisper to me when dawn is coming. It's really annoying, honestly.

My name is Elara, and I am a wood elf. But nobody at HK Sino-British College knows that. They just think I'm the quiet girl who always wear long sleeves even in summer and sit alone at lunch time under the old banyan tree.

The banyan tree is my favorite place in the whole school. Its roots twist like old fingers into the ground, and its canopy is so thick that you can't see the sky when you sit under it. Sometimes, when nobody is looking, I press my palm against its bark and feel it breathe. It remembers a time before concrete and MTR stations. It remembers when this island was all forest.

"Elara! Are you listening?"

I blink. Ms. Wong is staring at me from the front of the classroom. The whiteboard behind her is full of chemistry equations that look like alien language to me.

"Sorry, miss," I say. The whole class laughs a little. My face feels hot.

My friend Mei sits next to me and slides her notebook over. She wrote "PAY ATTENTION" in big letters with an angry face. I smile a little. Mei is the only person who really talk to me. She doesn't know my secret, but she knows I'm weird, and she doesn't care.

Being a wood elf in Hong Kong is... difficult. The city is so loud. All the time. Cars and construction and people shouting into their phones. My ears are slightly pointed — I hide them with my hair — and they are too sensitive. I can hear things humans can't. The hum of electricity in the walls. The heartbeat of a bird three floors down. The way the air sounds different before it rains.

In biology class, we learned about photosynthesis last week. Mr. Chan was explaining how plants make food from sunlight, and I almost laughed out loud. Because I can do that too. Not exactly the same way, but when I sit in the sun long enough, I feel my skin drink the light. My mother says it's why we don't need to eat as much as humans. We don't get energy from rice and dim sum. We get it from the earth and the sun.

But try explaining that to your classmates when they ask why you never finish your lunch at the canteen.

"You're so skinny! Do you have eating disorder?" Jenny asked me once. She wasn't being mean, just curious. But I didn't know what to say.

"I just... have fast metabolism," I said. It was the lie my mother told me to use.

The hardest part is P.E. class. We were running the 800-meter last month, and I accidentally ran it in 2 minutes and 15 seconds. The P.E. teacher, Mr. Lee, stared at me like I was a ghost.

"Elara, have you been training?" he asked.

"I... I used to run a lot at home," I stammered. Which was kind of true. I run through the forest near our apartment every night when no one can see me. I can run faster than any human, but I have to be careful. I have to slow myself down. I have to pretend to be tired when I'm not. I have to breathe hard even when my lungs feel fine.

It's exhausting, pretending to be something you're not.

There are other things too. Small things. The way flowers turn toward me when I walk past the flower shop in our neighborhood. The way stray cats follow me home like I'm their mother. The way my skin sometimes glows very faintly green when I'm really happy, and I have to cover it up and pretend I'm just blushing.

My mother is a wood elf too. She came to Hong Kong twenty years ago from a forest that doesn't exist on any human map. She fell in love with a human — my father — and chose to stay. She works as a herbalist in a small shop in Sham Shui Po. People think she sells traditional Chinese medicine. They don't know that some of her remedies are made with real magic.

"Never let them see what you are," she tells me every morning before I leave for school. "Humans are curious creatures. They fear what they don't understand."

But sometimes I wonder if she's wrong.

Last week, something happened that made me think maybe things don't have to be this way forever.

It was after school, and I was sitting under my banyan tree as usual. The school was mostly empty. I had my eyes closed and I was listening to the tree — it was telling me about the rain that would come tomorrow — when I heard footsteps.

I opened my eyes. It was a boy from my class named Tai. He's the quiet one who always draw in his sketchbook during class. He was standing a few meters away, staring at me.

"How long have you been sitting there?" I asked, feeling nervous.

"Five minutes," he said. "I was drawing you." He held up his sketchbook. In it, there was a picture of me sitting under the tree, and... my skin was glowing. Just slightly. Just the way it does when I'm at peace.

My heart stopped.

"You... you drew that?" I whispered.

He nodded. "Is it real? The glow? Or was it just the light?"

I didn't know what to say. I wanted to run. I wanted to disappear into the tree and never come out. But something in his eyes was not fear. It was wonder.

"It's just the light," I said. But my voice was shaking.

He looked at me for a long time. Then he said, "Okay." And he sat down next to me under the banyan tree, and he started drawing again.

We didn't say anything else. But he came back the next day. And the day after that. And every day since then, he sits with me under the tree after school. He draws. I listen to the wind. Sometimes he shows me his drawings. Sometimes we just exist in the same space, quietly.

He hasn't asked me about the glow again. But I think he knows. I think he sees something in me that other people don't. And maybe that's okay.

Maybe not everyone is afraid of what they don't understand.

Today is Friday. The banyan tree tells me it will rain at 4:15. It's 3:47 now. I'm sitting in English class, trying to write this essay about "who I am." The prompt says to be honest.

How can I be honest when my whole life is a secret?

I look out the window. The sky is getting dark. The trees are swaying. I can feel the rain coming in my bones, the way you feel a song before you hear it.

I pick up my pen and write:

"My name is Elara. I am sixteen years old. I am a student at HK Sino-British College. I like sitting under trees and listening to the wind. I am different from most people, but I am learning that different is not the same as wrong.

I don't know who I am yet. But I know I am growing."

The rain starts at exactly 4:15. I smile.

Some things you just know. [end of text]


